{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537370"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:16:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:16:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16023"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16023"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.22,0.02,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109052"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8714"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16023"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91418"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"4410"},{"type":"tags","id":"4420"},{"type":"tags","id":"4506"},{"type":"tags","id":"4507"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40684"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109052"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Birth Suite with her first pregnancy at 39 weeks gestation. She reports contractions occurring every 5-8 minutes for the past six hours. She noticed clear fluid leaking from her vagina four hours ago. She has no significant medical history and has had an uncomplicated pregnancy. She takes pregnancy multivitamins only. She reports normal fetal movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears comfortable between contractions. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. On vaginal examination, her cervix is 3 cm dilated, 50% effaced, and the vertex is at station -3. Clear amniotic fluid is visible. Cardiotocography shows reassuring features with contractions occurring two in ten minutes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this woman\u0027s stage of labour?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Latent first stage","Active first stage","Prelabour","Second stage","Transitional stage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman presents with features characteristic of latent phase labour, including irregular contractions and cervical dilatation less than 4 cm. The latent phase can last many hours, particularly in nulliparous women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELatent first stage\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as the period of irregular contractions accompanied by cervical change up to 4 cm dilatation. This phase involves cervical effacement and early dilatation. Women may experience varying degrees of pain and discomfort during this phase. There can be some variation in international guidelines in the definition of latent vs active labour - some international guidelines do not classify active labour until 6 cm dilation is reached. In Australia active labour is usually diagnosed after 4 cm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive first stage\u003C/strong\u003E begins when cervical dilatation reaches 4 cm and is accompanied by regular contractions. This woman\u0027s cervix is only 3 cm dilated with irregular contractions, making active labour unlikely. There can be some variation in international guidelines in the definition of latent vs active labour - some international guidelines do not classify active labour until 6cm dilation is reached. In Australia active labour is usually diagnosed after 4 cm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrelabour\u003C/strong\u003E refers to Braxton Hicks contractions without cervical change. This woman has documented cervical change, indicating she has progressed beyond prelabour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecond stage\u003C/strong\u003E begins at full cervical dilatation (10 cm) and ends with delivery of the baby. This is clearly not applicable given the early cervical findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransitional stage\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the period between active first stage and second stage, typically occurring between 8-10 cm dilatation. This woman\u0027s cervical dilatation is too early for this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile women in latent phase labour can often be managed at home, this woman has ruptured membranes which necessitates hospital admission for monitoring of maternal and fetal wellbeing, and consideration of prophylactic antibiotics if labour becomes prolonged.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The latent phase of labour is characterised by irregular contractions and cervical dilatation less than 4 cm.","Active labour begins when cervical dilatation reaches 4 cm with regular contractions.","Women in latent phase labour can often be managed at home with adequate support and pain relief if membranes are intact."],"references":["Hutchison J, Mahdy H, Hutchison J. Stages of labor. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 [cited 2024 Nov 21]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544290/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91418"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16023"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91418","links":{"self":